[
  {
    "type": "H1",
    "children": [
      {
        "text": "The Passive Voice of Responsibility"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "paragraph",
    "children": [
      {
        "text": "I want to start by stating that this essay is not for everyone.  I think there might very well be people out there whose circumstance really do force their hand, and there are things they just have to do.  And there are jobs where the consequence of on individual in action can have life and death effects.  But chances are this is not you.  And that means you "
      },
      {
        "text": "don't have to do anything",
        "Italic": true
      },
      {
        "text": "."
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "paragraph",
    "children": [
      {
        "text": ""
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "paragraph",
    "children": [
      {
        "text": "So I want to propose that if we "
      },
      {
        "text": "do not",
        "Bold": true
      },
      {
        "text": " have to do anything then we should stop saying that we have to do things.  I want to offer a two-step process to move away from \"have to\""
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "H2",
    "children": [
      {
        "text": "Example to Start With"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "paragraph",
    "children": [
      {
        "text": "Let's start with a few examples where one might use \"have to\" language:"
      }
    ]
  }
]

[
  {
    "type": "paragraph",
    "children": [
      {
        "text": "In both of these examples there is no doer there are only people that have things done to them, it's the passive voice of responsibility."
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "H2",
    "children": [
      {
        "text": "Step 1: Say What You Want"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "paragraph",
    "children": [
      {
        "text": "You are about to do something and you are choosing to do it. Start by saying this is what you want to do. \"Want\" might not feel like the right word, but if there is something else you want to do more, maybe you should do that instead. \n"
      }
    ]
  }
]

[
  {
    "type": "paragraph",
    "children": [
      {
        "text": "I want to reschedule our one on one"
      }
    ]
  }
]

[
  {
    "type": "paragraph",
    "children": [
      {
        "text": "I want to reschedule our one on one because I have a conflict with a client meet, if I miss that meeting this is a risk that the team will get off on the wrong foot."
      }
    ]
  }
]

[
  {
    "type": "paragraph",
    "children": [
      {
        "text": "In this step you are taking ownership of what is happening, you stop things from happening to you or happening around you.  This is good in and of itself, but it also leads us into our second step. "
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "paragraph",
    "children": [
      {
        "text": ""
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "paragraph",
    "children": [
      {
        "text": "As you do this you will most likely be very uncomfortable.  By making someone (in this case you) the actor, you will feel the need to explain why you want such things.  This is great! lean into and...  "
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "H2",
    "children": [
      {
        "text": "2. Explain Your Want"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "paragraph",
    "children": [
      {
        "text": "In step two we want to go ahead and justify your want, tell someone why you want what you do."
      }
    ]
  }
]

[
  {
    "type": "paragraph",
    "children": [
      {
        "text": "This now gives the person you are talking to context about the choices you are making.  It also opens the door for you to be "
      },
      {
        "data": {
          "openModal": true,
          "slatenode": {
            "href": "https://critter.blog/2021/02/09/say-things-that-can-be-wrong/"
          }
        },
        "type": "Link",
        "children": [
          {
            "text": "wrong"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "text": ".  It gives them the chance to say I hear that is important please hear me out on my want. Or to disagree with your assessment of the situation. In short, it gives them information and an invitation to engage."
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "H2",
    "children": [
      {
        "text": "Conclusion"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "paragraph",
    "children": [
      {
        "text": "In step one, you empowered yourself by establishing that your actions are yours, in step two you empower others by giving them the opening to talk about why you might be wrong.  "
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "paragraph",
    "children": [
      {
        "text": ""
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "paragraph",
    "children": [
      {
        "text": "Using \"have to\" might feel like a shortcut but in the end, it only shortcuts agency."
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "paragraph",
    "children": [
      {
        "text": "\n"
      }
    ]
  }
]

[
  {
    "type": "paragraph",
    "children": [
      {
        "text": "This work has to be done by Monday morning."
      }
    ]
  }
]

[
  {
    "type": "paragraph",
    "children": [
      {
        "text": "I have to reschedule our one on one."
      }
    ]
  }
]

